  <content>
    <title>AI Governance and Compliance</title>
    <summary>Comprehensive framework for AI governance, model risk management, and regulatory compliance in MLOps. Provides agent-executable gates, templates, prompts, and verification commands for EU AI Act + NIST AI RMF alignment.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>AI governance ensures AI systems are safe, compliant, ethical, explainable, and properly documented. It sits above MLOps to provide oversight and traceability across the entire AI lifecycle. For agents shipping AI features, governance is the gate that prevents legally exposed deployments (EU AI Act fines up to 35M EUR or 7% global turnover) and produces the technical file regulators require on demand.</p>
      <p>Market context (2025-2026): AI governance market grows at ~45.3% CAGR, projected to reach $5.8B by 2029. EU AI Act enters full enforcement in 2026. AI industry overall grows at ~30.6% CAGR (2025-2032). Regulatory exposure is no longer optional for any product touching the EU market or making decisions about people.</p>
      <p>Regulatory landscape the agent must align with simultaneously:</p>
      <list>
        <item>EU AI Act — risk-based regulation; mandatory for EU market access; tiers: Unacceptable / High / Limited / Minimal.</item>
        <item>NIST AI RMF 1.0 — risk-management framework; voluntary for US federal vendors; widely adopted as a de-facto baseline.</item>
        <item>ISO/IEC 42001 — AI management system; global certification; 6-12 month process; enterprise-priced.</item>
        <item>ISO/IEC 38507 — board-level AI governance; complementary to 42001.</item>
        <item>SOC 2 Type II — security controls; expected by SaaS buyers regardless of AI scope.</item>
        <item>GDPR — applies to all PII flowing into training and inference; right to deletion + lawful basis.</item>
        <item>EEOC Four-Fifths Rule (US employment) — disparate impact threshold for hiring/promotion AI.</item>
        <item>FDA SaMD / EU MDR — medical-device path for diagnostic AI.</item>
      </list>
      <p>Core pillars the agent operationalizes: (1) Model Governance — registration, versioning, approval workflow, retirement; (2) Audit Trails — immutable logs of decisions, training data provenance, hyperparameters, retraining events; (3) Responsible AI — bias detection + mitigation, fairness monitoring, explainability, human oversight; (4) Data Governance — consent management, retention policies, right-to-deletion, quality monitoring.</p>
      <p>Target operational metrics: model documentation coverage 100%, audit trail completeness 100%, bias assessment per deployment, human review rate 100% on high-risk decisions, time-to-compliance-report &lt; 1 day, model approval cycle time &lt; 5 days, incident response time &lt; 4 hours, audit finding resolution &lt; 30 days.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <p>Apply this methodology whenever an autonomous agent is about to deploy, retrain, or materially change a model that lands in production AND any of the following are true: it makes decisions about people (credit, hiring, healthcare, education, insurance), it ships into the EU market, it processes PII, or it is integrated into a safety-critical workflow. If none apply, fall back to lightweight logging only.</p>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Proof-of-concept or internal tool with no production traffic — governance overhead is disproportionate.</item>
        <item>Minimal-risk AI (spam filter, recommender with no legal/financial impact) — no formal governance required by EU AI Act.</item>
        <item>Pre-revenue startup — lightweight logging suffices; formal governance adds friction without regulatory necessity.</item>
        <item>No assigned DRI — governance without ownership degrades into checkbox theater.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <how-to>
      <step>1. Classify risk tier per EU AI Act using the prompt with purpose=risk-classification. Output one of: unacceptable | high | limited | minimal. Persist the result to `governance/risk_tier.json`.</step>
      <step>2. If tier is `unacceptable`, abort the deployment and surface the reason. If `high`, all downstream gates are MANDATORY. If `limited`, only transparency disclosure is required. If `minimal`, log and skip.</step>
      <step>3. Generate or update the model card from training artifacts using the model-card prompt. Save to `docs/model-cards/{model-id}-{version}.md`.</step>
      <step>4. Generate the data sheet for the training dataset using the datasheet prompt. Save to `docs/datasheets/{dataset}-{date}.md`.</step>
      <step>5. Run the bias gate (`bias_gate.py`) on a held-out eval set with the actual production demographic distribution. Block if disparate impact &lt; 0.8 OR demographic parity difference &gt; 0.1.</step>
      <step>6. Compute SHAP feature attributions on a 100-row sample. Persist attributions to `governance/shap_{model_id}.parquet`. Block if any single feature owns &gt; 60% of total attribution mass (proxy-leakage signal).</step>
      <step>7. Validate the audit log schema is migrated and append-only (see SQL template). Run a probe insert + attempt update; the update MUST fail.</step>
      <step>8. Write a deployment event to `audit/model_deployments.jsonl` with action=`eval_pass` or `eval_fail`. Use atomic writes (write to tmp + rename).</step>
      <step>9. Require human sign-off for `high` tier: open a review issue with the conformity-assessment template populated and block deployment until issue is closed with the `governance:approved` label.</step>
      <step>10. Trigger deployment. Immediately register the model in MLflow (or equivalent) with full lineage: training_data_uri, code_commit, hyperparameters, eval_metrics, fairness_metrics, risk_tier.</step>
      <step>11. Configure monitoring: drift (Evidently), fairness re-check (Fairlearn weekly), incident webhook → on-call.</step>
      <step>12. Schedule periodic reviews: monthly performance, quarterly bias re-assessment, annual full audit.</step>
    </how-to>

    <checklist>
      <check>Model card generated and committed to `docs/model-cards/`.</check>
      <check>Data sheet generated and committed to `docs/datasheets/`.</check>
      <check>Risk assessment artifact saved to `governance/risk_assessment.md`.</check>
      <check>Intended use and out-of-scope uses documented in the model card.</check>
      <check>Version history block in model card updated with the new version row.</check>
      <check>Fairness metrics calculated across all protected attributes in the eval set.</check>
      <check>Disparate impact ratio &gt; 0.8 for every protected group comparison.</check>
      <check>Equal opportunity difference &lt; 0.1 for every protected group comparison.</check>
      <check>SHAP global feature importance and local explanations for 5 sampled predictions saved.</check>
      <check>Plain-language explanation template populated for end users.</check>
      <check>Data lineage traceable from raw source to training artifact (MLflow run_id or DVC tag).</check>
      <check>Consent / lawful basis documented for every personal data field.</check>
      <check>PII anonymized or pseudonymized; raw PII NOT in training features.</check>
      <check>Retention period defined and enforced (TTL field on audit table).</check>
      <check>RBAC configured for model registry, audit log, and inference endpoint.</check>
      <check>TLS in transit; encryption at rest (AES-256 or KMS-managed) verified.</check>
      <check>Vulnerability scan run on serving image; zero critical findings.</check>
      <check>Rate limiting + input validation on the inference endpoint.</check>
      <check>Human review queue wired for high-risk decisions; escalation path defined.</check>
      <check>EU AI Act risk classification recorded; if `high`, conformity assessment populated.</check>
      <check>Append-only audit log writes verified by a probe insert + failed update test.</check>
      <check>Rollback plan documented and the previous model version still loadable.</check>
      <check>Monthly / quarterly / annual review schedule registered in calendar/cron.</check>
      <check>Vendor-supplied AI components (foundation models, APIs) have DPA + sub-processor list on file.</check>
    </checklist>

    <commands>
      <command name="install-tools">pip install fairlearn==0.10.* aif360 shap lime mlflow evidently great-expectations langfuse</command>
      <command name="run-bias-gate">python -m governance.bias_gate --eval data/eval.parquet --sensitive gender,age_group,ethnicity --max-dpd 0.1 --min-di 0.8</command>
      <command name="generate-shap">python -m governance.shap_report --model artifacts/model.pkl --sample data/eval.parquet --out governance/shap_{model_id}.parquet</command>
      <command name="register-mlflow">mlflow models register --model-uri runs:/$RUN_ID/model --name {model_name}</command>
      <command name="audit-append">python -m governance.audit_log --action eval_pass --model-id {model_id} --metadata @eval.json</command>
      <command name="probe-immutability">psql -c "UPDATE ai_decision_audit SET output_prediction='{}' WHERE id=(SELECT id FROM ai_decision_audit LIMIT 1);" ; echo "expected: ERROR"</command>
      <command name="drift-check">evidently report --reference data/baseline.parquet --current data/last7d.parquet --output governance/drift_{date}.html</command>
      <command name="validate-eu-ai-act">python -m governance.eu_ai_act_check --metadata model-meta.json --requires articles 9,10,11,12,13,14,15</command>
      <command name="run-quality-gate">python -m governance.deploy_gate --model-id {id} --tier high --eval-results eval.json --strict</command>
    </commands>

    <verify>
      <step>1. Run `python scripts/validate-methodology-xml.py` on the methodology.xml itself to confirm structural compliance (single-source check before applying methodology).</step>
      <step>2. Confirm `governance/risk_tier.json` exists and contains one of {unacceptable, high, limited, minimal}.</step>
      <step>3. Confirm `docs/model-cards/{model-id}-{version}.md` exists and contains all 9 sections (Model Details, Intended Use, Training Data, Evaluation, Limitations, Ethical Considerations, How to Use, Citation, References).</step>
      <step>4. Run `python -m governance.bias_gate --eval data/eval.parquet --sensitive ...` and assert exit code 0 and `gate_status == "pass"`.</step>
      <step>5. Run `psql -c "\d+ ai_decision_audit"` and verify `created_at` has a TRIGGER or table is configured `WITH (autovacuum_enabled = false, fillfactor = 100)`. Then attempt an UPDATE on an existing row — it MUST raise an error from the immutability trigger.</step>
      <step>6. Tail `audit/model_deployments.jsonl` and confirm the latest line has the current commit SHA, model_id, and `action == "deploy"`.</step>
      <step>7. Open the MLflow UI: confirm the new model version is registered with stage=Production and links to its run, dataset, and risk_tier tag.</step>
      <step>8. For high-risk: confirm the GitHub/Linear issue carries the `governance:approved` label and the approver is NOT the deploying agent.</step>
      <step>9. Trigger one synthetic prediction through the production endpoint and grep the audit log for the matching trace_id within 10 seconds.</step>
      <step>10. Run `evidently` against a same-distribution sample and confirm drift_score &lt; 0.05 baseline (sanity: monitoring is wired).</step>
    </verify>

    <rules>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Block any deployment where EU AI Act tier is `high` and the conformity assessment file is missing or incomplete.</statement>
        <rationale>Article 16-21 require the technical file PRIOR to placing the system on the market. Post-hoc remediation is not legally permitted.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Audit log inserts MUST be atomic (write-then-rename for files, single INSERT for SQL); never write JSON line-by-line via streaming append without flush+fsync.</statement>
        <rationale>Crashes mid-write produce truncated lines that break audit reconstruction; auditors reject corrupt logs.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Governance agents MUST NOT self-approve their own model deployments at high-risk tier; require an external human approver identity captured in the audit record.</statement>
        <rationale>Article 14 (human oversight) and ISO/IEC 42001 require independent review before deployment of high-risk AI.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Bias evaluation MUST run on a held-out set drawn from the production data distribution, not the original benchmark dataset.</statement>
        <rationale>Benchmark distributions diverge from production; benchmark fairness does not predict production fairness.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Disparate impact ratio must be &gt; 0.8 OR a documented exception with sign-off from compliance officer must be on file.</statement>
        <rationale>EEOC four-fifths rule and general fairness practice; below 0.8 = adverse impact requiring justification.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Sensitive features (race, gender, age, ethnicity) MUST NOT be used directly as model inputs unless explicitly required and justified in the risk assessment.</statement>
        <rationale>Avoids direct discrimination; proxy detection done via SHAP feature-importance scan instead.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </rules>

    <prompt purpose="risk-classification"><![CDATA[
You are an EU AI Act compliance auditor. Classify the system below into one of:
- unacceptable (Article 5: social scoring, manipulative, real-time biometric in public)
- high (Annex III: employment, education, credit, law enforcement, critical infra, etc.)
- limited (transparency obligation; e.g. chatbots, deepfakes)
- minimal (everything else)

System name: {system_name}
Purpose: {purpose}
Domain: {domain}
Users: {user_types}
Decision impact: {decision_impact}
Functionality: {functionality_description}

Output strict JSON:
{
  "risk_tier": "unacceptable|high|limited|minimal",
  "reasoning": "1-2 sentences citing the article",
  "annex_iii_category": "<category or null>",
  "required_articles": ["9","10","11","12","13","14","15"],
  "transparency_obligations": ["..."],
  "blocking_issues": ["..."],
  "recommended_actions": ["..."]
}
Cite specific EU AI Act articles. Be conservative — when uncertain between two tiers, pick the more restrictive.
]]></prompt>

    <prompt purpose="model-card-generation"><![CDATA[
Generate a Hugging Face-format model card from the artifacts below. Output strict markdown.

Model Name: {{model_name}}
Model Type: {{model_type}}
Framework: {{framework}}
Training Dataset: {{dataset_description}}
Training Date: {{training_date}}
Performance Metrics: {{metrics_json}}
Feature Information: {{feature_descriptions}}

Sections required (use markdown ## headings):
1. Model Details — name, version, type, framework, release date, owner
2. Intended Use — primary use cases, intended users, out-of-scope uses
3. Training Data — dataset description, size, demographics, preprocessing
4. Evaluation — metrics with context, subgroup performance
5. Limitations — known failure modes, performance degradation conditions
6. Ethical Considerations — potential harms, mitigations, human oversight needs
7. How to Use — minimal code snippet
8. Citation — BibTeX or canonical citation form
9. References — links to data sheet, risk assessment, audit logs

Be specific. Avoid generic statements. For every missing field, write `[MISSING: <field>]` so it can be grep'd later.
]]></prompt>

    <prompt purpose="bias-analysis"><![CDATA[
You are a fairness auditor. Analyze the metrics below and produce a structured report.

Model: {{model_name}}
Task: {{task_type}}
Protected attributes: {{protected_attributes}}
Fairness metrics: {{metrics_json}}

Provide:
1. Metric interpretation — what each metric means in this context.
2. Bias assessment — overall fairness rating (PASS / REVIEW / FAIL) and most concerning disparities.
3. Four-fifths rule analysis — for each protected attribute, compute selection-rate ratio min/max and flag if &lt; 0.8.
4. Root-cause hypotheses — likely causes (training data imbalance, feature proxies, label noise).
5. Recommendations — immediate actions, long-term improvements, monitoring suggestions.

Output JSON:
{
  "overall_status": "PASS|REVIEW|FAIL",
  "metrics_interpretation": {...},
  "four_fifths_results": {...},
  "concerns": [...],
  "actions": [{"priority": "P0|P1|P2", "owner": "...", "action": "..."}]
}
]]></prompt>

    <prompt purpose="conformity-assessment"><![CDATA[
Generate an EU AI Act conformity assessment document for a high-risk system.

System: {{system_name}}
Provider: {{provider}}
Annex III category: {{annex_iii_category}}
Version: {{version}}
Existing docs:
- Model Card: {{model_card_summary}}
- Risk Assessment: {{risk_assessment_summary}}
- Testing Results: {{testing_summary}}

Address each article in turn. For each, output: STATUS (Complete | Partial | Missing) + Evidence + Gaps.
- Article 9 (Risk Management System)
- Article 10 (Data Governance)
- Article 11 (Technical Documentation)
- Article 12 (Record-Keeping)
- Article 13 (Transparency)
- Article 14 (Human Oversight)
- Article 15 (Accuracy and Robustness)

Final block: Conformity Declaration (compliance statement + responsible parties + signatures).
Flag any gap with a P0 tag — these must be remediated BEFORE deployment.
]]></prompt>

    <prompt purpose="decision-explanation"><![CDATA[
Generate a plain-language explanation for an audience of {{audience}} (technical | non-technical | regulatory).

Model: {{model_name}}
Prediction: {{prediction}}
Confidence: {{confidence}}
Feature values: {{feature_values}}
SHAP values: {{shap_values}}

Sections:
1. Plain-language summary — what the model predicted, confidence in context.
2. Key factors — top 3-5 with direction (positive/negative) and relative importance.
3. Counterfactual — minimum input change required for a different outcome.
4. Confidence context — when to trust vs question the prediction.
5. Limitations — factors the model cannot consider.

Adjust depth based on audience. For regulatory: cite the relevant article and link to model card.
]]></prompt>

    <prompt purpose="drift-analysis"><![CDATA[
You are an MLOps drift analyst. Analyze drift patterns and produce an incident-grade report.

Model: {{model_name}}
Baseline period: {{baseline_period}}
Current period: {{current_period}}

Feature drift: {{feature_drift_metrics}}
Prediction drift: {{prediction_drift_metrics}}
Performance drift: {{performance_metrics}}

Output sections:
1. Drift Summary — overall severity (Low/Medium/High/Critical), most affected features, trend direction.
2. Root Cause Analysis — likely causes (seasonality, data-source changes, upstream schema drift, model decay).
3. Impact Assessment — performance effect, business impact estimate, compliance implications.
4. Recommendations — immediate actions (if Critical), investigation priorities, retraining triggers, monitoring tweaks.
5. Timeline — when drift became significant + projected trajectory if uncorrected.

Include specific threshold comparisons and statistical significance. Output strict JSON with the five sections as keys.
]]></prompt>

    <prompt purpose="incident-summary"><![CDATA[
You are an AI incident manager. Summarize an incident for both technical and executive audiences.

Incident ID: {{incident_id}}
System: {{system_name}}
Detection time: {{detection_time}}
Severity: {{severity}}
Description: {{incident_description}}
Timeline: {{event_timeline}}
Actions taken: {{response_actions}}

Output sections (markdown):
1. Executive Summary — one paragraph + key impact metrics + current status.
2. Incident Description — what happened, how detected, systems affected.
3. Impact Analysis — users/decisions affected, business + regulatory impact.
4. Root Cause — technical root cause + contributing factors + prevention gaps.
5. Response Effectiveness — what worked, what could improve, response-time analysis.
6. Remediation Status — immediate fixes + long-term fixes + prevention measures.
7. Lessons Learned — key takeaways + process improvements + documentation updates.

Open with the executive summary; the rest follows for the technical reader.
]]></prompt>

    <prompt purpose="governance-review"><![CDATA[
You are the chair of the AI Governance Board. Review the model below and decide.

Model: {{model_name}}
Version: {{version}}
Purpose: {{purpose}}
Requestor: {{requestor}}
Documentation:
- Model Card: {{model_card_status}}
- Data Sheet: {{datasheet_status}}
- Risk Assessment: {{risk_assessment_status}}
- Test Results: {{test_results}}
- Fairness Analysis: {{fairness_status}}

Performance metrics: {{metrics}}

Provide:
1. Documentation Completeness — checklist with Status (Complete/Partial/Missing) per item; list critical gaps.
2. Technical Assessment — performance adequacy, robustness concerns, scalability.
3. Compliance Assessment — regulatory alignment, policy compliance, audit readiness.
4. Risk Assessment — key risks, mitigation adequacy, residual risk acceptance.
5. Fairness Assessment — bias-testing completeness, concerning disparities, mitigation effectiveness.
6. Recommendation — APPROVE / APPROVE WITH CONDITIONS / REJECT, conditions, follow-up.

Be specific about approval conditions and rejection reasons. Cite the model-card and risk-assessment files explicitly.
]]></prompt>

    <prompt purpose="audit-response"><![CDATA[
You are the AI compliance officer responding to an external audit.

Auditor: {{auditor}}
Audit type: {{audit_type}}
System: {{system_name}}
Audit questions: {{questions}}
Available documentation: {{documentation_list}}

For each audit question, output:
1. Direct Answer — clear, factual; reference specific documentation.
2. Evidence — document names + sections, specific metrics, dates, version numbers.
3. Supporting Context — additional relevant info, process descriptions, governance measures.
4. Gaps Identified — areas requiring follow-up, remediation plans if applicable.

Use precise language. Avoid speculation. If information is unavailable, state clearly what documentation would be needed and assign owner + due date.
]]></prompt>

    <example type="good" title="Credit Scoring Model — full governance stack">
      <description>Financial institution deploying ML model for credit risk assessment. Risk Level: High (EU AI Act, Annex III §5(b)).</description>
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# bias monitoring on each scoring batch
from fairlearn.metrics import MetricFrame, selection_rate
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

PROTECTED = ['gender', 'age_group', 'ethnicity']

def monitor_batch(y_true, y_pred, df) -> dict:
    mf = MetricFrame(
        metrics={'accuracy': accuracy_score, 'selection_rate': selection_rate},
        y_true=y_true, y_pred=y_pred,
        sensitive_features=df[PROTECTED],
    )
    alerts = []
    for feature in PROTECTED:
        rates = mf.by_group['selection_rate'].xs(feature, level=0) \
                if hasattr(mf.by_group['selection_rate'], 'xs') \
                else mf.by_group['selection_rate']
        di = rates.min() / rates.max() if rates.max() > 0 else 0
        if di < 0.8:
            alerts.append({"feature": feature, "disparate_impact": di})
    return {"frame": mf.by_group.to_dict(), "alerts": alerts}
]]></code>
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# audit-trail wrapper around scoring
from langfuse import Langfuse
from datetime import datetime

langfuse = Langfuse()

def score_application(application: dict) -> dict:
    trace = langfuse.trace(
        name="credit-scoring",
        metadata={
            "model_version": "v2.3.1",
            "application_id": application['id'],
            "timestamp": datetime.utcnow().isoformat() + "Z",
        },
    )
    trace.span(name="input-features", input=anonymize_pii(application))
    score = model.predict(application)
    trace.span(
        name="model-output",
        output={
            "score": score,
            "decision": "approved" if score > THRESHOLD else "denied",
            "shap_values": get_shap_explanation(application),
            "top_factors": get_top_factors(application),
        },
    )
    return {"score": score, "trace_id": trace.id}
]]></code>
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# human-in-loop escalation rules
ESCALATION_RULES = {
    "borderline_score": lambda s: 0.45 < s < 0.55,
    "high_value_loan": lambda app: app["amount"] > 100_000,
    "first_application": lambda app: app["history_months"] == 0,
}

def needs_human_review(application: dict, score: float) -> bool:
    for name, rule in ESCALATION_RULES.items():
        if name == "borderline_score":
            if rule(score): return True
        else:
            if rule(application): return True
    return False
]]></code>
      <note>Documentation set required: model card (`docs/model-cards/credit-score-v2.3.1.md`), data sheet (`docs/datasheets/credit-features-2024.md`), risk assessment (`docs/risk/credit-model-risk-v2.md`), conformity assessment (`docs/compliance/eu-ai-act-credit.md`).</note>
    </example>

    <example type="good" title="Healthcare Diagnostic AI — model card excerpt">
      <description>Medical imaging AI for radiology assistance (lung nodule detection). Risk Level: High (medical device, FDA/CE-marked).</description>
      <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
## Model Details
- Name: LungScan-AI
- Version: 3.1.0
- Release Date: 2025-09-15
- Type: Convolutional Neural Network (3D U-Net variant)
- Modality: CT scans

## Intended Use
- Primary: Assist radiologists in detecting lung nodules.
- Users: Licensed radiologists, trained technicians.
- Environment: Hospital PACS integration.
- NOT for: Primary diagnosis without radiologist review.

## Training Data
- Source: 5 academic medical centers (de-identified).
- Volume: 50,000 CT scans, 180,000 annotated nodules.
- Demographics: Age 35-85, 52% male, multi-ethnic.
- Annotation: Board-certified radiologists (3x consensus).

## Performance Metrics
| Metric      | Overall | <6mm  | 6-8mm | >8mm  |
|-------------|---------|-------|-------|-------|
| Sensitivity | 94.2%   | 88.1% | 96.3% | 98.7% |
| Specificity | 91.8%   | 89.2% | 93.1% | 95.4% |
| AUC         | 0.967   | 0.932 | 0.971 | 0.989 |

## Limitations
- Performance degrades on motion-artifact scans.
- Not validated for pediatric populations.
- Requires specific CT protocols (see technical docs).
- May miss ground-glass nodules in certain orientations.

## Ethical Considerations
- Human radiologist must verify all findings.
- Not for use as sole diagnostic criterion.
- Regular bias monitoring across demographics.
]]></code>
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# Continuous monitoring metrics (Prometheus-style)
from prometheus_client import Counter, Histogram, Gauge

predictions_total = Counter('model_predictions_total', 'Total predictions',
                            ['model_version', 'prediction_class'])
inference_latency = Histogram('model_inference_seconds', 'Inference latency',
                              ['model_version'])
data_drift_score = Gauge('model_data_drift', 'Data drift score (KL divergence)',
                         ['model_version', 'feature'])
subgroup_accuracy = Gauge('model_subgroup_accuracy', 'Accuracy by demographic',
                          ['model_version', 'demographic', 'group'])

DRIFT_THRESHOLD = 0.15
ACCURACY_DROP_THRESHOLD = 0.05
]]></code>
    </example>

    <example type="good" title="HR Resume Screening — bias prevention">
      <description>AI-assisted resume screening for initial candidate filtering. Risk Level: High (employment, EU AI Act Annex III §4(a); also US Title VII).</description>
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# bias-prevention preprocessor
class FairResumeScorer:
    def preprocess(self, resume_text: str) -> dict:
        text = self.redact_names(resume_text)            # name = demographic proxy
        text = self.normalize_dates(text)                # year-of-graduation = age proxy
        text = self.normalize_institutions(text)         # institution prestige proxy
        return self.extract_features(text)

    def predict_with_fairness(self, features: dict) -> dict:
        raw = self.model.predict(features)
        adj = self.calibrator.adjust(raw, features.get('inferred_group')) \
              if self.calibrator else raw
        return {"raw_score": raw, "adjusted_score": adj,
                "fairness_adjustment": raw - adj}

    def audit_batch(self, predictions, actuals, demographics):
        from aif360.metrics import BinaryLabelDatasetMetric
        metrics = {}
        for attr in self.protected_attributes:
            ds = self.create_aif360_dataset(predictions, actuals, demographics, attr)
            m = BinaryLabelDatasetMetric(
                ds,
                privileged_groups=[{attr: 1}],
                unprivileged_groups=[{attr: 0}],
            )
            metrics[attr] = {
                "statistical_parity": m.statistical_parity_difference(),
                "disparate_impact": m.disparate_impact(),
                "equal_opportunity": m.equal_opportunity_difference(),
            }
        return metrics
]]></code>
      <code lang="markdown"><![CDATA[
## Adverse Impact Analysis — Q4 2025

### Selection Rates by Group
| Group     | Apps   | Selected | Rate  | vs. Baseline |
|-----------|--------|----------|-------|--------------|
| Overall   | 10,000 | 2,500    | 25.0% | -            |
| Male      | 5,500  | 1,400    | 25.5% | +2%          |
| Female    | 4,500  | 1,100    | 24.4% | -2%          |
| Age 20-35 | 6,000  | 1,550    | 25.8% | +3%          |
| Age 35-50 | 3,000  | 750      | 25.0% | 0%           |
| Age 50+   | 1,000  | 200      | 20.0% | -20%         |

### Four-Fifths Rule
| Comparison         | Impact Ratio | Status            |
|--------------------|--------------|-------------------|
| Female / Male      | 0.96         | PASS (>0.8)       |
| Age 50+ / Age 20-35| 0.78         | REVIEW (borderline) |

### Remediation
1. Review feature weights for `experience_years`.
2. Audit training data for age-correlated patterns.
3. Pilot age-blind scoring path.
]]></code>
    </example>

    <example type="good" title="Customer Service Chatbot — limited-risk transparency">
      <description>LLM-powered chatbot handling customer inquiries. Risk level: limited (Article 52 transparency).</description>
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
class CustomerServiceBot:
    def respond(self, user_message: str, context: dict) -> dict:
        # Article 52: user must know they are talking to an AI
        disclosure = None
        if context.get('first_message', True):
            disclosure = ("I'm an AI assistant. I can help with general questions; "
                          "for complex issues I can connect you with a human agent.")
        response = self.guardrails.invoke(
            llm=self.llm,
            messages=[{"role": "user", "content": user_message}],
            config={
                "prohibited_topics": ["medical_advice", "legal_advice"],
                "pii_handling": "mask",
                "escalation_triggers": ["speak to human", "complaint", "lawsuit"],
            },
        )
        self.audit_log.record(
            session_id=context['session_id'],
            input=user_message,
            output=response['content'],
            guardrails_triggered=response.get('triggered_guardrails', []),
            escalated=response.get('escalated', False),
        )
        return {"disclosure": disclosure, "response": response['content'],
                "escalated": response.get('escalated', False)}
]]></code>
