    <section name="implementation-phases">
      <p>Roll out governance in four phases. Each phase is a separate SDD feature; the agent finishes one before starting the next so partial work never lands in production half-governed.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Phase 1 — Assessment: inventory all AI systems (spreadsheet or MLflow), classify each by risk tier, gap-analyze against EU AI Act + NIST AI RMF, prioritize remediation by risk × exposure.</item>
        <item>Phase 2 — Infrastructure: deploy governance platform (MLflow registry + Langfuse traces + Evidently monitoring), configure append-only audit logging (Postgres trigger or S3 object-lock), set up model registry with stage transitions Production/Staging/Archived, implement RBAC (model owners + reviewers + readers).</item>
        <item>Phase 3 — Processes: define approval workflows (Pull Request → governance review → label `governance:approved` → deploy), create documentation templates (model card / datasheet / risk assessment), train teams (onboarding doc + quarterly refresh), establish review cadence (monthly perf, quarterly bias, annual full audit).</item>
        <item>Phase 4 — Continuous: monitor bias and drift (Evidently webhook → on-call), regular compliance audits (internal monthly + external annual), update for new regulations (subscribe to EUR-Lex + NIST changelog), report to stakeholders (governance dashboard + quarterly board memo).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="risk-categories">
      <p>Catalogue and quantify every risk before the model ships. The risk register is the single source of truth that every audit response references.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Technical risks — model drift degrading performance, training/serving skew, data quality issues, security vulnerabilities (model extraction, prompt injection, adversarial inputs), infrastructure failures, dependency rot.</item>
        <item>Compliance risks — regulatory non-compliance, documentation gaps, audit failures, unauthorized deployments, changes deployed without approval, sub-processor changes not surfaced.</item>
        <item>Ethical risks — algorithmic bias and direct discrimination, indirect discrimination via proxy features, privacy violations (PII leakage in prompts, training-data memorization), lack of transparency, uncontrolled AI behavior (autonomous loops without circuit breakers).</item>
        <item>Operational risks — single points of failure (one model owner, one DRI), tribal knowledge not documented, rollback path untested, monitoring blind spots (e.g. missing protected-attribute column).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="integration-points">
      <p>Hook governance into existing systems instead of building parallel infrastructure. Each integration is a single contract.</p>
      <list>
        <item>MLOps pipeline — pre-deployment gates (bias gate, doc gate, conformity gate); fail-fast on any block.</item>
        <item>CI/CD — compliance checks as required GitHub/GitLab status checks; merge blocked without `governance:approved` label on high-risk PRs.</item>
        <item>Data catalog — lineage tracking; every model in registry links to its dataset URI in the catalog.</item>
        <item>SIEM — security monitoring; audit log ships to SIEM; access-violation alerts.</item>
        <item>GRC platform — risk reporting; quarterly export of risk register + compliance status.</item>
        <item>Issue tracker — every governance review opens an issue; closure with `governance:approved` label is the gate signal.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Wire governance as a deployment gate, not a post-hoc audit. The agent runs the gate on every model deployment event and blocks on any failure.</p>
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import json, datetime
from pathlib import Path

AUDIT_LOG = Path("audit/model_deployments.jsonl")

def log_deployment_event(
    model_id: str,
    action: str,                  # deploy | retire | eval_pass | eval_fail
    metadata: dict,
    actor: str = "agent",
) -> None:
    AUDIT_LOG.parent.mkdir(exist_ok=True)
    event = {
        "timestamp": datetime.datetime.utcnow().isoformat() + "Z",
        "model_id": model_id,
        "action": action,
        "actor": actor,
        "metadata": metadata,
    }
    # atomic append: write tmp + rename
    tmp = AUDIT_LOG.with_suffix(".jsonl.tmp")
    with open(tmp, "a") as f:
        f.write(json.dumps(event) + "\n")
        f.flush()
        import os; os.fsync(f.fileno())
    # for true append-only on POSIX, use O_APPEND + fsync; rename only for new files
    tmp.rename(AUDIT_LOG) if not AUDIT_LOG.exists() else None
]]></code>
      <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# bias gate (≤30 lines)
from fairlearn.metrics import (
    MetricFrame, demographic_parity_difference,
)
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score

def bias_gate(y_true, y_pred, sensitive_features, max_dpd: float = 0.1) -> dict:
    mf = MetricFrame(
        metrics=accuracy_score,
        y_true=y_true, y_pred=y_pred,
        sensitive_features=sensitive_features,
    )
    dpd = demographic_parity_difference(
        y_true, y_pred, sensitive_features=sensitive_features,
    )
    passed = abs(dpd) <= max_dpd
    return {
        "gate_status": "pass" if passed else "fail",
        "demographic_parity_difference": round(float(dpd), 4),
        "threshold": max_dpd,
        "accuracy_by_group": mf.by_group.to_dict(),
    }
]]></code>
      <p>Recommended subagent: `faion-sdd-executor-agent` — drives the compliance check sequence as SDD tasks with quality gates and stops on any failure.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools">
      <p>Standard governance toolbelt. All open-source unless noted; install via `pip`.</p>
      <list>
        <item>`fairlearn` — bias assessment + mitigation. `pip install fairlearn`. Docs: fairlearn.org</item>
        <item>`aif360` — IBM AI Fairness 360, broader fairness metrics. `pip install aif360`. Docs: github.com/Trusted-AI/AIF360</item>
        <item>`shap` — SHAP feature attributions. `pip install shap`. Docs: shap.readthedocs.io</item>
        <item>`lime` — local model-agnostic explanations. `pip install lime`. Docs: github.com/marcotcr/lime</item>
        <item>`mlflow` — model registry, lineage, experiment logging. `pip install mlflow`. Docs: mlflow.org</item>
        <item>`great-expectations` — data quality validation. `pip install great-expectations`. Docs: greatexpectations.io</item>
        <item>`evidently` — drift, fairness in production. `pip install evidently`. Docs: evidentlyai.com</item>
        <item>`langfuse` — LLM trace-level observability and audit. `pip install langfuse`. Docs: langfuse.com</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="services-and-platforms">
      <list>
        <item>Weights &amp; Biases — SaaS model registry + lineage; agent-friendly REST API.</item>
        <item>MLflow — OSS, self-hosted; model registry; artifact storage; agent-friendly.</item>
        <item>Credo AI — SaaS; EU AI Act alignment; policy workflows; partial agent support.</item>
        <item>DataRobot — Enterprise SaaS MLOps + governance; partial API access.</item>
        <item>Langfuse — OSS/SaaS; LLM observability; trace-level audit for LLM decisions.</item>
        <item>Braintrust — SaaS; eval + audit trails for LLM-based systems.</item>
        <item>Evidently — OSS/SaaS; production monitoring; drift + bias alerts via webhook.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <antipattern>
      <description>Documentation written after deployment, not before — the model card describes what was shipped instead of being a deployment gate.</description>
      <reason>EU AI Act Article 11 + 16 require the technical file before placement on the market; post-hoc docs are not legally compliant.</reason>
    </antipattern>
    <antipattern>
      <description>Bias evaluation against benchmark dataset (e.g. UCI Adult) instead of production distribution.</description>
      <reason>Benchmark fairness does not predict production fairness; a model that passes on benchmark may exhibit adverse impact on real users.</reason>
    </antipattern>
    <antipattern>
      <description>Agent self-approves its own deployment via a config flag.</description>
      <reason>Article 14 (human oversight) requires independent review for high-risk AI; self-approval voids the legal compliance claim.</reason>
    </antipattern>
    <antipattern>
      <description>Audit log writes via streaming append without flush+fsync.</description>
      <reason>Crash mid-write produces a truncated final line; auditors reject corrupt logs and the deployment loses traceability.</reason>
    </antipattern>
    <antipattern>
      <description>SHAP explanations cached and re-served instead of computed per-prediction for high-risk decisions.</description>
      <reason>Each prediction has a unique attribution profile; serving stale explanations misleads regulators and end users.</reason>
    </antipattern>

    <warning>EU AI Act high-risk classification triggers documentation requirements BEFORE deployment, not after. Block the deploy and remediate; never ship and "fix the docs next sprint".</warning>
    <warning>Sensitive features (race, gender, age, ethnicity) must NOT be used directly as model inputs unless explicitly justified in the risk assessment. Run a SHAP-based proxy scan to detect indirect leakage from correlated features (e.g. ZIP code → race).</warning>
    <warning>ISO/IEC 42001 certification takes 6-12 months and is enterprise-priced. For solopreneur-scale projects, target the lighter NIST AI RMF + EU AI Act technical file instead.</warning>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Integrate governance as a deployment gate in CI/CD; prevention beats remediation.</item>
        <item>Maintain a model inventory (spreadsheet or MLflow registry) with: model_id, use_case, risk_tier, data_sources, DRI.</item>
        <item>Use append-only audit logs — never update or delete past entries; immutability is a legal requirement in some jurisdictions.</item>
        <item>Separate model documentation responsibility from model development; conflicts of interest produce rubber-stamp docs.</item>
        <item>For EU AI Act high-risk: maintain a technical file = model card + datasheet + eval results + risk assessment + conformity declaration.</item>
        <item>Run bias assessments on production data distribution, not a benchmark.</item>
        <item>Review governance metrics on a fixed cadence (monthly/per-deploy), not only on incidents.</item>
        <item>Scale governance investment to actual risk exposure, not regulatory checkbox compliance.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Governance agents must not self-approve their own deployments — gate must be reviewed by a human for high-risk systems.</item>
        <item>Bias metrics require a sensitive-attribute column in the eval dataset; agents must verify it exists before running assessment.</item>
        <item>Audit log writes must be transactional — atomic file writes (write tmp + fsync + rename) prevent corruption.</item>
        <item>SHAP for transformers is approximate and slow; budget time and consider sampling.</item>
        <item>EU AI Act "high-risk" classification triggers documentation requirements before deployment, not after — block if docs incomplete.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop approval is legally mandated for high-risk system deployments — never auto-deploy without documented human sign-off.</item>
        <item>Generic Fairlearn defaults assume binary protected attributes; multi-class attributes require per-pair audits.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="enterprise-platforms-comparison">
      <p>Off-the-shelf platforms when build-vs-buy tilts toward buy. All have partial agent integration; verify the API surface before committing.</p>
      <list>
        <item>DataRobot — unified governance + auto compliance reports; best for enterprise MLOps with mixed model types; expensive; partial REST API.</item>
        <item>Domino Data Lab — audit trails + reproducibility focus; strong in regulated industries (banking, pharma); good API.</item>
        <item>Credo AI — policy workflows and EU AI Act alignment; compliance-first orgs; limited API surface for autonomous agents.</item>
        <item>Weights &amp; Biases — experiment tracking + lineage; excellent for ML teams already using W&amp;B; full SDK + REST API; solid agent fit.</item>
        <item>MLflow (OSS) — self-hosted; model registry, artifact storage, experiment logging; the default open-source choice; full Python API.</item>
        <item>Langfuse (OSS/SaaS) — LLM-specific trace observability; the right tool for LLM-based products where prompts and tool calls form the audit trail.</item>
        <item>Braintrust — eval + audit trails for LLM systems; strong for offline eval pipelines.</item>
        <item>Fiddler AI — explainability + monitoring; strong for tabular models in finance/insurance.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="monitoring-playbook">
      <p>Steady-state monitoring after deployment. The agent runs each at the cadence below and fans out alerts when thresholds breach.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Per-prediction (synchronous): inference latency p50/p95/p99, error rate, input validation failures, rate-limit triggers, guardrail trips. Alert if p95 latency &gt; 2x baseline.</item>
        <item>Hourly: prediction-distribution drift vs trailing 24h baseline, prediction count vs forecast (anomaly detection), guardrail-trip rate. Alert if drift score &gt; 0.10.</item>
        <item>Daily: feature-distribution drift (KL divergence per feature), data-quality metrics (missing rates, type violations, range violations). Alert if any feature KL &gt; 0.15.</item>
        <item>Weekly: subgroup accuracy by protected attribute, fairness re-check (Fairlearn), false-positive rate per segment. Alert if any subgroup accuracy drops &gt; 5pp from baseline.</item>
        <item>Monthly: full performance review vs holdout, bias re-assessment, SHAP-stability check (top features have not shifted by more than 1 rank). Open quarterly review issue.</item>
        <item>Quarterly: bias re-audit + documentation refresh (model card version bump), compliance scan against latest regulatory text, third-party-component review.</item>
        <item>Annually: comprehensive governance audit, regulatory alignment review (EU AI Act + NIST + ISO updates), policy refresh, team training refresh, vendor review.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-selection">
      <p>Pick the right model for each governance sub-task. Default to Opus for anything strategic or legally exposed.</p>
      <list>
        <item>Governance framework design / risk classification / conformity assessment — Opus (strategic, high-stakes, regulatory citations required).</item>
        <item>Policy development / model card drafting / datasheet drafting — Sonnet (document creation, structured output).</item>
        <item>Audit response / fairness-metric interpretation — Sonnet (compliance checking, structured output).</item>
        <item>Drift-report rephrasing / incident summary expansion — Sonnet (text transformation).</item>
        <item>Routine status checks / templated comments — Haiku (cheap, deterministic).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

